Overview
The combination of Newton’s laws of motion and Newton’s law of universal gravitation form the foundation of classical mechanics, which explains the motion of ordinary physical objects under everyday conditions. Newton’s first law of motion, or the law of inertia, states an object at rest remains at rest and an object in motion remains in motion at constant speed unless acted on by an unbalanced force. Newton’s second law of motion states that net force is equal to mass times acceleration. Newton’s third law of motion states for every action force there is an equal and opposite reaction force. In this investigation, you will explore Newton’s three laws of motion, giving you a better understanding of objects in motion.

Outcomes
• Demonstrate Newton’s first law of motion. • Determine the force required to move an object up an incline. • Calculate the acceleration of an object moving up an incline. • Verify Newton’s second law of motion.

