Background
Newton’s Laws of Motion Classical mechanics, also referred to as Newtonian mechanics, is the area of physics built on the works of Sir Isaac Newton (1643– 1727), comprising Newton’s three laws of motion and Newton’s law of universal gravitation. Newton’s laws of motion are given designations to aid in recalling them: Newton’s first law of motion is the law of inertia, Newton’s second law of motion is F = ma, and Newton’s third law of motion is action − reaction. The core of classical mechanics is the combination of these mathematical laws and principles: Newton’s first law of motion, Newton’s second law of motion, Newton’s third law of motion, Newton’s law of universal gravitation, law of conservation of energy, law of conservation of momentum, and Bernoulli’s principle.
Newton’s first law of motion states that an object at rest will remain at rest or in uniform motion in a straight line unless acted upon by a net

external force. This statement describes inertia, the tendency of an object to resist changes in motion; mass SI unit of kilogram [kg] is the quantitative measure of inertia. The International Committee for Weights and Measures has defined the kilogram by defining Planck’s constant to be exactly 6.62607015×10−34 kg m2 s−1, effectively defining the kilogram in terms of the second and the meter.
Newton’s second law of motion is the mathematical relationship between force, mass, and acceleration or between force and the derivative with respect to time of momentum as shown in Equation 1.
Equation 1.
Force, F, is a vector with SI units of newtons [N = kg m/s2], and acceleration, a, is also a vector quantity with SI units of m/s2. Momentum, p, is equal to mass times velocity and is a vector with SI units of kg m/s. The force is the net external force and is applicable to a wide range of physical phenomena, but it is not a fundamental principle like the conservation laws. When the net force is defined as the rate of change of momentum, the relationship net force equals mass times acceleration will only apply if the mass is constant. A change in the acceleration of an object with a fixed mass will result in a corresponding change in the net force, such as when the acceleration of an object increases and the mass remains constant, the acceleration change was caused by an increase in the net force.

