EXTENSION ACTIVITY

Extension Activity
Newton’s Laws of Motion Demonstrated Using a Balloon Rocket
Background
A rocket’s movement depends on Newton’s third law of motion, which states for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction. When a rocket blows out gas at high speed in one direction (action force), the rocket is pushed in the opposite direction (reaction force). When there is a force on an object in one direction, another force is acting on the other object in the opposite direction. The gas pushes against the rocket, and the rocket pushes back just as hard against the gas.
In the extension activity, a rocket will be simulated using a balloon on a string. The balloon will be attached to a drinking straw that has been strung through a long length of string allowing the attached balloon to travel along the string. The balloon will be filled with air that will be allowed to escape, propelling the balloon forward.
Objectives
• Observe action and reaction forces using a balloon traveling along a string.
• Compare the distances a balloon travels on string when filled with different amounts of air.

