3. Blow up the balloon so it is half full of air; use the measuring tape to determine the circumference of the balloon at the largest section and adjust the volume of air until you have the circumference of a half-full balloon.

4. Hold the end of the balloon closed but do not tie it. Attach the balloon underneath the straw with a piece of transparent tape.

5.

Begin recording your video, then

release your hold on the balloon.

6. The force of the air being propelled out of the balloon will force it along the string. After the balloon stops you can stop recording.

7. Measure how far from its starting position the balloon traveled. Measure from the mark made near the back of the chair to the location where the same end of the straw stopped. Record this measurement in Data Table E2 for Trial 1.

8. Carefully remove the balloon from the straw; pull the straw back to the starting position. Ensure the string is still tight, and repeat Steps 3 through 7 (you do not need to video each trial) for Trial 2 for a half-full balloon.
9. Carefully remove the balloon from the straw; pull the straw back to the starting position. Ensure the string is still tight, and repeat Steps 3 through 7 (you do not need to video each trial) for Trial 3 for a half-full balloon.
10. Review the measurements you made for the 3 trials for consistency. It may be difficult to get identical conditions for each trial, but you should have measurements that are not widely varied. Repeat trials if needed to get consistent data.
11. Clean your work space.

